  "summary": "Blackstone and Boyd Carrington discuss the nature of crime and impulse before touring Nayton Manor, a Tudor-period estate. Carrington explains that his uncle, Sir Evelyn, was a recluse who left him a large inheritance. During the tour of the manor and its gardens, Carrington shares personal details regarding his grief over his late wife, who died of alcoholism, and a missed romantic opportunity with a much younger woman. He also discusses local residents, including Colonel Lethbridge and his business-minded wife, as well as Norton, a man who prefers birdwatching to hunting.\n\nMeanwhile, at Styles, an atmosphere of unease persists among the guests. Blackstone expresses frustration to Hercule Poirot about being kept in the dark regarding the identity of \"X.\" Poirot reprimands Blackstone, explaining that the investigation is not a game of guessing identities, but a mission to save lives. Poirot clarifies that the primary objective is to determine who the next victim will be. When Blackstone suggests there must be a connection between the victim and X, Poirot explains that the genius of X lies in the fact that the connection is so subtle that it remains undiscovered.",
